        <td>With a liver biopsy (BYE-op-see), the<br>
        physician is able to examine a small piece<br>
        of tissue from your liver for signs of<br>
        damage or disease. This procedure<br>
        involves using a special needle to remove<br>
        tissue from the liver. The physician<br>
        decides to do a liver biopsy after tests<br>
        suggest that the liver does not work<br>
        properly. For example, a blood test<br>
        might show that your blood contains<br>
        higher than normal levels of liver<br>
        enzymes or too much iron or copper. An<br>
        x-ray could suggest that the liver is<br>
        swollen. Looking at liver tissue itself is<br>
        the best way to determine whether the<br>
        liver is healthy. <br>
